before.enText: of food, especially bread and cake

data.enText: no longer fresh and therefore unpleasant to eat

data.chText: 不新鲜的；（空气）污浊的；（烟味）难闻的
陈腐的；没有新意的；老掉牙的
data.enText: something that is stale has been said or done too many times before and is no longer interesting or exciting

data.chText: 他们的婚姻已了无热情。
（因持续做某事时间太长）厌倦的，腻烦的
data.enText: a person who is stale has done the same thing for too long and so is unable to do it well or produce any new ideas

data.chText: 在那个岗位干了十年之后，她觉得腻了，需要换换工作。
data.enText: After ten years in the job, she felt stale and needed a change.

word_means: 使陈旧；使没有味道；用坏；变陈旧

means: 使陈旧；使没有味道；用坏；变陈旧

tr: lacking freshness, palatability, or showing deterioration from age

value.def: Stale food is no longer fresh or good to eat.

example.ex: Their daily diet consisted of a lump of stale bread, a bowl of rice and stale water.
example.tran: 他们的日常饮食包括一块不新鲜的面包、一碗米饭和变味的水。

value.def: Stale air or a stale smells is unpleasant because it is no longer fresh.

example.ex: A layer of smoke hung low in the stale air.
example.tran: 一层烟雾低悬在污浊的空气中。

value.def: If you feel stale, you are bored because you have no new ideas or enthusiasm for what you are doing.

example.ex: I believe in progression, in taking risks, in never getting stale.
example.tran: 我崇尚进取、冒险和永不倦怠。

value.def: If you say that a place, an activity, or an idea is stale, you mean that it has become boring because it is always the same.

example.ex: Her relationship with Mark has become stale...
example.tran: 她和马克之间已经没有新鲜感了。

example.ex: The Government, he said, were sticking to stale ideas.
example.tran: 他说政府仍在抱残守缺。

value.tran: (地方、活动或观点)令人厌倦的，缺乏新鲜感的
